[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Pamela Zave's classification scheme for organizing research in software requirements includes various categories that help structure the field and guide research efforts. One such category is the study of requirements elicitation techniques, which focuses on methods to effectively gather and understand the needs and constraints of stakeholders.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Pamela Zave has proposed a classification scheme for organizing the different types of research that go on in the area of software requirements (P. Zave (1997). “Classification of research efforts in requirements engineering.” ACM Computing Surveys, 29(4): 315 - 321).",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Research in requirements elicitation is of great use to software developers because it provides systematic approaches to capture the diverse and often conflicting views of stakeholders, ensuring that the final requirements accurately reflect the needs of users, customers, and other participants. This research helps developers avoid misunderstandings and incomplete requirements, which are common causes of project failure.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Each stakeholder has a particular view of the system and how it should work, and often these views conflict. One of the many skills of a requirements analyst is the ability to understand each view and capture the requirements in a way that reflects the concerns of each participant.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "One example of research cited by Zave in this category is the Volere requirements process model (Robertson and Robertson 1999), which provides a structured approach to eliciting requirements from multiple sources, including stakeholders, templates, and libraries of requirements from related systems. This model addresses the problem of incomplete or overlooked requirements by offering a comprehensive framework for gathering and organizing requirements.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The Volere requirements process model (Robertson and Robertson 1999), as shown in Figure 4.2, suggests some additional sources for requirements, such as templates and libraries of requirements from related systems that we have developed.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The results presented by the Volere model include improved completeness and clarity of requirements, better communication among stakeholders, and a more manageable requirements specification process. This ultimately leads to higher quality software that better meets user needs and reduces costly changes during development.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In addition to interviewing stakeholders, other means of eliciting requirements include the old system continues to be used because it provides some critical function that the designers of the new system overlooked The Volere requirements process model (Robertson and Robertson 1999), as shown in Figure 4.2, suggests some additional sources for requirements, such as templates and libraries of requirements from related systems that we have developed.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Training and documentation are essential for supporting system delivery, but they must be well-designed and maintained to be effective.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Training can be done in many ways. No matter how training is provided, it must offer information to users and operators at all times, not just when the system is first delivered.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "One common issue is that users often do not read manuals or documentation thoroughly, which can interfere with their effective use of the software system.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In fact, one study showed that only 10% to 15% of the users in an intensive training program read the manual at all (Scharer 1983). Six months later, no one else had read the user manual, and replacement pages with revised information had not been filed in the manual.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To improve training and documentation aids and prevent interference with software usage, the following changes could be made:",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "Training and documentation should be designed to be easily accessible and user-friendly",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Documents. Formal documentation accompanies every system and supports training. The documents contain all the information needed to use the system properly and efficiently. Existing in separate manuals or online, documents are accessible to users and operators as the system is functioning.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Use well-defined icons and online help to make system functions clear and easy to understand, reducing reliance on manuals.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Users may prefer well-defined icons, online help, demonstrations, and classes to learn how the system works. Icons and Online Help. A system can be designed so that its interface with the user makes system functions clear and easy to understand.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Integrate training and documentation software with the regular system software to provide seamless access.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "training and documentation software should be integrated with the regular system software",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Plan and maintain updates to training and documentation early and continuously to keep information current and relevant.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Moreover, updates to training and documentation can be planned early. The development team can put in place ways to access updates from a central location or to download them to users automatically from the Internet or Web sites.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Tailor documentation to the needs of different audiences, such as users, operators, programmers, and analysts, to ensure relevance and clarity.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "training and documentation modules and documents should take into account the varying needs of different audiences: users, operators, customers, programmers, and others who work with or interact with the system",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Considering the Audience. A computer-based system is used by a variety of people. In addition to users and operators, other members of the development team and the customer staff read documentation when questions arise or changes are proposed and made.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The paper by Janice Singer and Timothy Lethbridge on methods for studying maintenance activities involves observing the work practices of software engineers engaged in maintenance projects.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Researchers with the Institute for Information Technology of the National Research Council, Canada, study maintenance by observing the work practices of software engineers who are engaged in maintenance projects. A paper by Janice Singer and Timothy Lethbridge summarizes the methods they use to collect this type of data.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "From the viewpoint of a software maintainer, the data collection methods are likely to be somewhat disruptive because maintenance work often involves complex problem-solving, understanding legacy code, and balancing management and technical needs, which requires concentration and continuity.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "At the same time, the system usually becomes more complex as a result of two things. First, as one fault is corrected, the fix may itself be introducing new system faults. Second, as corrections are made, the system structure changes. Because many repairs are made with the limited purpose of solving a particular problem, the coupling and cohesion of components, as well as the inheritance structure of an object-oriented system, are often degraded.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Management Priorities. The maintenance team weighs the desires of the customer's management against the system's needs. Management priorities often override technical ones;managers sometimes view maintaining and enhancing as more important than building new applications. In other words, companies must sometimes focus on business as usual, instead of investigating new alternatives. But as management encourages maintainers to repair an old system, users are clamoring for new functions or a new system. Similarly, the rush to get a product to market may encourage us, as either developers or maintainers, to implement a quick, inelegant, poorly tested change, rather than take the time to follow good software engineering practice.The result is a patched product that is difficult to understand and repair later.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "However, the maintainer stands to gain from participating in such a study because the research aims to develop better ways to measure maintainability, predict fault sources, and build tools to assist in the maintenance process, which could make their work easier and more effective in the future.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Maintenance is a ripe area of research. Many of our maintenance activities could be made easier or more effective if we were better at predicting the likely sources of faults. Researchers are looking for better ways to measure maintainability based on product information; they are developing new models to show us the interconnections among products, processes, and resources. Similarly, the models will help us know how much effort is needed to maintain a system and when it is appropriate to retire a legacy system or rejuvenate it.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Work continues on building tools to assist us in the maintenance process. Reengineering tools, change control and configuration management repositories, and project history databases are likely to become more sophisticated as researchers build prototypes based on empirical data.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Additionally, participating in such studies may help improve the recognition of the maintainer's skill and the importance of their role, potentially improving morale and productivity.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A major reason for low morale is the second-class status often accorded the maintenance team. Programmers sometimes think that it takes more skill to design and develop a system than to keep it running. However, as we have seen, maintenance programmers handle problems that developers never see. Maintainers are skilled not only in writing code but also in working with users, in anticipating change, and in sleuthing. Great skill and perseverance are required to track a problem to its source, to understand the inner workings of a large system, and to modify that system's structure, code, and documentation.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Empirical studies in software engineering often involve human subjects because they need to assess the usefulness of development techniques for the people who will use them. Unlike studies that focus solely on technical aspects, such as algorithm performance, studies involving human subjects must consider human variability, team size, collaboration styles, and working environments. For example, research on improvement issues emphasizes the importance of understanding human factors to determine whether quality and schedule goals will be met, and to design techniques and tools that leverage this variability to advantage.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Finally, software engineering researchers should jump into human factors research with both feet. We can understand more about resources issues such as team size, collaboration styles, and what makes a good working environment by learning from studies already performed in the social sciences. Then, we can assess which results apply to software engineers. Most researchers admit that human variability is a key factor in determining whether quality and schedule goals will be met; a better understanding of that variability will help us design techniques and tools to use that variability to our advantage.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A recent empirical software study using human subjects would likely involve methods such as case studies, field studies, or replicated controlled experiments, which practitioners value highly for their relevance to real environments. These studies differ from purely technical studies because they require direct interaction with practitioners and consideration of organizational and evidential factors that influence technology transfer. For instance, technology transfer is promoted when a new technology is easy to use, well-packaged, and clearly beneficial to the project team, which are aspects that can only be evaluated through studies involving human subjects.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "techniques such as case studies, field studies, and replicated controlled experiments were considered to be important to the decision-making process in choosing a new technology. On the other hand, researchers prefer to perform studies involving reproducible validation methods that can be used in isolation in the laboratory, such as theoretical proof, static analysis, and simulation. They discounted methods that required interacting directly with practitioners. In other words, most researchers shunned the very methods that are most valued by practitioners: case studies, field studies, and experiments.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Technology transfer inhibitors and promoters fall into three categories: technological, organizational, and evidential. For example, technology transfer is inhibited by lack of packaging, by lack of relationship to a pressing technical or business problem, and by difficulty of use and understanding. By contrast, a new technology can be promoted with tools, a well-understood context, and an understanding of clear potential benefit to those on the project now or who will use the resulting product later. In other words, the technology is easier to transfer if it is easy to use and easy to see how it will help.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The context documents discuss the adoption and transfer of new software engineering technologies, which can include software processes, tools, or specific techniques.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In fact, we may need multiple models of diffusion, including iteration, based on the characteristics of the technology, the adopters, and the evidence.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The anticipated users of new technologies are categorized into adopter types such as innovators, early adopters, early majority, late majority, and laggards, as described in the documents.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Innovators tend to rely on technical journals and reports from researchers and technical experts. Early adopters in turn ask the innovators to confirm a technology's credibility. Early- and late-majority members ask others in their social system, often by word of mouth or benchmarking visits.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The documents describe attributes of new technologies that affect adoption, including compatibility, complexity, trialability, observability, and relative advantage, which influence different adopter types differently.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "- ◊ Compatibility: To what degree is the new technology consistent with existing values, past experiences, and needs of potential adopters?... - ◊ Complexity: To what degree is the new technology easy to understand and use?... - ◊ Trialability: Can the new technology be experimented with on a limited basis?... - ◊ Observability: Are the results of using the technology visible to others?... - The technology's attributes. Rogers suggests that the relevant attributes are - ◊ Relative advantage: To what degree is the new technology better than what is already available?",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Arguments about a technology's effectiveness include technical superiority, tangible evidence of the whole product, impact on the company, and market advantages, which correspond to different adopter concerns.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Innovators answer this question in technical terms: is it faster, architecturally superior, or more maintainable? Early adopters look for tangible evidence about the 'whole product.' Early-majority adopters seek information about the impact on the company, while late-majority adopters look at how the technology will increase market share.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The categories of evidence proposed by Schum, as described in section 14.2, include compatibility, complexity, trialability, observability, communication channels, social system, diffusion efforts, and relative advantage, which can be used to classify the arguments for technology effectiveness.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Technology transfer inhibitors and promoters fall into three categories: technological, organizational, and evidential... - ◊ Compatibility: To what degree is the new technology consistent with existing values, past experiences, and needs of potential adopters?... - ◊ Complexity: To what degree is the new technology easy to understand and use?... - ◊ Trialability: Can the new technology be experimented with on a limited basis?... - ◊ Observability: Are the results of using the technology visible to others?... - The nature of the communication channels used to increase awareness and knowledge of the technology... - The nature of the social system in which the potential user operates... - The extent of efforts to diffuse the technology throughout an organization... - The technology's attributes. Rogers suggests that the relevant attributes are - ◊ Relative advantage: To what degree is the new technology better than what is already available?",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The documents emphasize that compelling evidence alone is insufficient for adoption; packaging, user support, and marketing efforts are also critical to make the technology easier to understand and use, thus facilitating broader diffusion.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "However, compelling evidence is not enough to ensure technology adoption. The marketing world tells us how to package and support the technology to make it 'friendlier' and easier to understand and use. For example, tools and supporting written material go a long way in assisting a user to adopt a new technique or process.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A paper describing an organization's practical experience with a particular technology typically measures success by evaluating whether the technology solves the intended problem, its commercial viability, and the time it takes for the technology to become accepted practice.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "To know whether a technology is successful, we want to look at whether it solves a problem, whether it is commercially viable, and how long it takes for the technology to become accepted practice.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The kinds of evidence presented to support the evaluation of effectiveness include surveys, case studies, experiments, feature analysis, and other techniques that examine the technology itself and the body of evidence to determine if it is conflicting, consistent, and objective.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We should also identify promoters and inhibitors, so that we know who or what is likely to help or hinder technology adoption and effectiveness. ... we look at the situations in which the technology has been used, compare the old ways to the new ways, and determine (using surveys, case studies, experiments, feature analysis, and other techniques) whether the evidence is conflicting, consistent, and objective.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The evidence is classified according to categories such as compatibility, complexity, trialability, and observability, which reflect how different audiences perceive and evaluate the technology.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "- ◊ Compatibility: To what degree is the new technology consistent with existing values, past experiences, and needs of potential adopters? ... - ◊ Complexity: To what degree is the new technology easy to understand and use? ... - ◊ Trialability: Can the new technology be experimented with on a limited basis? ... - ◊ Observability: Are the results of using the technology visible to others?",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Different audiences such as innovators, early adopters, and mainstream market members look for different types of evidence, ranging from a focus on the technology itself to the company and market aspects, which helps in designing studies to provide relevant evidence.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Figure 14.2 summarizes the types of evidence appealing to different audiences. The lower-left quadrant reflects innovators' interests, where the focus is primarily on the technology itself. Early adopters turn their attention to the broader notion of product, while mainstream market members are more interested in the company and the market.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

